---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Editorial Team | divorcesettlementcalc.com';
const description = 'The editorial team behind divorcesettlementcalc.com — family law and divorce litigation specialists reviewing calculator methodology and guide content.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>All calculator methodology and guide content on divorcesettlementcalc.com is written and reviewed by The Click Lab&rsquo;s editorial team before publication. Our editorial standards require that factual claims be traceable to primary sources — statutes, published judicial opinions, or government data — and that calculator formulas be documented transparently on the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.</p>

  <h2>Family Law &amp; Divorce Litigation Practice</h2>
  <p>Our editorial team leads editorial oversight for divorcesettlementcalc.com. With a background in family law paralegal work and a focus on asset division and spousal support litigation, the team has spent over a decade supporting attorneys through contested divorce proceedings involving complex marital estates, business valuation disputes, and multi-state property division questions. That practical work in litigation support &mdash; reviewing financial disclosure packages, tracking case law developments across equitable distribution and community property states, and monitoring QDRO implementation outcomes &mdash; informs the editorial standards applied to every page on this site.</p>
  <p>This side of the team reviews the calculator methodology for consistency with current family law practice, monitors statutory and case law changes that affect the model&rsquo;s core assumptions, and edits all guide content for accuracy, clarity, and appropriate scope. A persistent emphasis in this editorial work: communicating what a calculator can and cannot tell you, and ensuring readers understand when professional legal counsel is necessary rather than optional.</p>

  <h2>Divorce Finance &amp; Settlement Research</h2>
  <p>Our team also contributes research and writing for divorcesettlementcalc.com, focusing on the financial mechanics of divorce settlement: how property classification works in practice, how spousal support calculations vary across jurisdictions, how retirement account divisions are structured and executed, and how tax law interacts with asset transfers incident to divorce. This research background spans published family law reviews, state-specific judicial surveys, and practitioner literature on settlement negotiation strategy in contested divorces.</p>
  <p>This side of the team writes the guide content and FAQ responses, with an emphasis on making technically complex material accessible without losing the nuance that makes the information useful.</p>

  <h2>Editorial Standards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Every factual claim is sourced to a primary authority (statute, regulation, or published judicial decision).</li>
    <li>Calculator formulas are documented in full on the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.</li>
    <li>Pages are reviewed and updated when family law statutes or significant case law developments affect the accuracy of the content.</li>
    <li>No sponsored content, paid placements, or advertiser influence on editorial decisions.</li>
    <li>All content is for informational purposes only and does not constitute legal advice. Readers with live divorce proceedings should consult a licensed family law attorney in their jurisdiction.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Corrections</h2>
  <p>Found an error or outdated information? <a href="/contact/">Contact us</a> and we will review it promptly. We take accuracy seriously and correct confirmed errors as quickly as possible.</p>
</BaseLayout>
